Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.650 --> 00:00:03.190
If you followed some of the
mathematics, and some of the

00:00:03.190 --> 00:00:06.590
thermodynamic principles in the
last several videos, what

00:00:06.590 --> 00:00:10.130
occurs in this video might
just blow your mind.

00:00:10.130 --> 00:00:12.570
So not to set expectations
too high, let's just

00:00:12.570 --> 00:00:14.506
start off with it.

00:00:14.506 --> 00:00:17.160
So let's say I have
a container.

00:00:17.160 --> 00:00:19.990
And in that container,
I have gas particles.

00:00:22.650 --> 00:00:25.480
Inside of that container,
they're bouncing around like

00:00:25.480 --> 00:00:29.000
gas particles tend to do,
creating some pressure on the

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:30.760
container of a certain volume.

00:00:30.760 --> 00:00:32.784
And let's say I have
n particles.

00:00:36.520 --> 00:00:38.920
Now, each of these particles
could be

00:00:38.920 --> 00:00:40.860
in x different states.

00:00:40.860 --> 00:00:42.110
Let me write that down.

00:00:56.420 --> 00:00:57.800
What do I mean by state?

00:00:57.800 --> 00:00:59.640
Well, let's say I
take particle A.

00:00:59.640 --> 00:01:01.840
Let me make particle A
a different color.

00:01:01.840 --> 00:01:05.080
Particle A could be down here
in this corner, and it could

00:01:05.080 --> 00:01:06.810
have some velocity like that.

00:01:06.810 --> 00:01:08.190
It could also be in that
corner and have a

00:01:08.190 --> 00:01:08.940
velocity like that.

00:01:08.940 --> 00:01:10.080
Those would be two
different states.

00:01:10.080 --> 00:01:12.070
It could be up here, and have
a velocity like that.

00:01:12.070 --> 00:01:14.050
It could be there and have
a velocity like that.

00:01:14.050 --> 00:01:16.260
If you were to add up all the
different states, and there

00:01:16.260 --> 00:01:20.340
would be a gazillion, of
them, you would get x.

00:01:20.340 --> 00:01:22.550
That blue particle could have
x different states.

00:01:22.550 --> 00:01:23.470
You don't know.

00:01:23.470 --> 00:01:24.740
We're just saying, look.

00:01:24.740 --> 00:01:25.545
I have this container.

00:01:25.545 --> 00:01:26.470
It's got n particles.

00:01:26.470 --> 00:01:28.670
So we just know that each
of them could be

00:01:28.670 --> 00:01:30.330
in x different states.

00:01:30.330 --> 00:01:33.620
Now, if each of them can be in
x different states, how many

00:01:33.620 --> 00:01:37.950
total configurations are there
for the system as a whole?

00:01:37.950 --> 00:01:42.080
Well, particle A could be in x
different states, and then

00:01:42.080 --> 00:01:44.990
particle B could be in
x different places.

00:01:44.990 --> 00:01:46.340
So times x.

00:01:46.340 --> 00:01:48.880
If we just had two particles,
then you would multiply all

00:01:48.880 --> 00:01:51.130
the different places where
X could be times all the

00:01:51.130 --> 00:01:54.970
different places where the red
particle could be, then you'd

00:01:54.970 --> 00:01:57.290
get all the different
configurations for the system.

00:01:57.290 --> 00:01:58.570
But we don't have just
two particles.

00:01:58.570 --> 00:02:00.260
We have n particles.

00:02:00.260 --> 00:02:04.690
So for every particle, you'd
multiply it times the number

00:02:04.690 --> 00:02:06.840
of states it could have,
and you do that

00:02:06.840 --> 00:02:09.729
a total of n times.

00:02:09.729 --> 00:02:13.290
And this is really just
combinatorics here.

00:02:13.290 --> 00:02:14.540
You do it n times.

00:02:14.540 --> 00:02:16.840
This system would have
n configurations.

00:02:16.840 --> 00:02:19.940
For example, if I had two
particles, each particle had

00:02:19.940 --> 00:02:22.860
three different potential
states, how many different

00:02:22.860 --> 00:02:24.330
configurations could there be?

00:02:24.330 --> 00:02:28.210
Well, for every three that one
particle could have, the other

00:02:28.210 --> 00:02:30.540
one could have three different
states, so you'd have nine

00:02:30.540 --> 00:02:31.190
different states.

00:02:31.190 --> 00:02:31.970
You'd multiply them.

00:02:31.970 --> 00:02:33.690
If you had another particle with
three different states,

00:02:33.690 --> 00:02:35.050
you'd multiply that by
three, so you have

00:02:35.050 --> 00:02:36.530
27 different states.

00:02:36.530 --> 00:02:38.660
Here we have n particles.

00:02:38.660 --> 00:02:41.020
Each of them could be in
x different states.

00:02:41.020 --> 00:02:43.380
So the total number of
configurations we have for our

00:02:43.380 --> 00:02:47.580
system-- x times itself n times
is just x to the n.

00:02:47.580 --> 00:02:53.790
So we have x to the n states
in our system.

00:02:53.790 --> 00:02:57.530
Now, let's say that we like
thinking about how many states

00:02:57.530 --> 00:03:00.080
a system can have. Certain
states have less-- for

00:03:00.080 --> 00:03:02.340
example, if I had fewer
particles, I would have fewer

00:03:02.340 --> 00:03:03.510
potential states.

00:03:03.510 --> 00:03:07.140
Or maybe if I had a smaller
container, I would also have

00:03:07.140 --> 00:03:08.240
fewer potential states.

00:03:08.240 --> 00:03:10.510
There would be fewer potential
places for our little

00:03:10.510 --> 00:03:12.320
particles to exist.

00:03:12.320 --> 00:03:17.180
So I want to create some type
of state variable that tells

00:03:17.180 --> 00:03:21.230
me, well, how many states
can my system be in?

00:03:21.230 --> 00:03:24.030
So this is kind of a macrostate
variable.

00:03:24.030 --> 00:03:28.040
It tells me, how many states
can my system be in?

00:03:28.040 --> 00:03:31.730
And let's call it
s for states.

00:03:31.730 --> 00:03:33.640
For the first time in
thermodynamics, we're actually

00:03:33.640 --> 00:03:38.050
using a letter that in some way
is related to what we're

00:03:38.050 --> 00:03:39.930
actually trying to measure.

00:03:39.930 --> 00:03:41.650
s for states.

00:03:41.650 --> 00:03:44.750
And since the states, they can
grow really large, let's say I

00:03:44.750 --> 00:03:47.350
like to take the logarithm
of the number of states.

00:03:47.350 --> 00:03:49.860
Now this is just how I'm
defining my state variable.

00:03:49.860 --> 00:03:51.120
I get to define it.

00:03:51.120 --> 00:03:53.970
So I get to put a logarithm
out front.

00:03:53.970 --> 00:03:56.790
So let me just put
a logarithm.

00:03:56.790 --> 00:03:59.810
So in this case, it would be the
logarithm of my number of

00:03:59.810 --> 00:04:05.690
states-- so it would be x to the
n, where this is number of

00:04:05.690 --> 00:04:06.940
potential states.

00:04:10.250 --> 00:04:12.330
And you know, we need some
kind of scaling factor.

00:04:12.330 --> 00:04:14.710
Maybe I'll change the
units eventually.

00:04:14.710 --> 00:04:18.519
So let me put a little
constant out front.

00:04:18.519 --> 00:04:21.709
Every good formula needs
a constant to

00:04:21.709 --> 00:04:22.790
get our units right.

00:04:22.790 --> 00:04:24.500
I'll make that a lowercase k.

00:04:24.500 --> 00:04:25.580
So that's my definition.

00:04:25.580 --> 00:04:28.950
I call this my state variable.

00:04:28.950 --> 00:04:31.470
If you give me a system, I
should, in theory, be able to

00:04:31.470 --> 00:04:35.170
tell you how many states
the system can take on.

00:04:35.170 --> 00:04:35.760
Fair enough.

00:04:35.760 --> 00:04:38.760
So let me close that
box right there.

00:04:38.760 --> 00:04:46.160
Now let's say that I were to
take my box that I had-- let

00:04:46.160 --> 00:04:49.350
me copy and paste it.

00:04:49.350 --> 00:04:51.790
I take that box.

00:04:51.790 --> 00:04:53.860
And it just so happens
that there was an

00:04:53.860 --> 00:04:56.450
adjacent box next to it.

00:04:56.450 --> 00:05:00.120
They share this wall.

00:05:00.120 --> 00:05:02.505
They're identical in size,
although what I just drew

00:05:02.505 --> 00:05:03.560
isn't identical in size.

00:05:03.560 --> 00:05:04.290
But they're close enough.

00:05:04.290 --> 00:05:05.820
They're identical in size.

00:05:05.820 --> 00:05:09.210
And what I do, is I blow
away this wall.

00:05:09.210 --> 00:05:11.010
I just evaporate it,
all of a sudden.

00:05:11.010 --> 00:05:12.680
It just disappears.

00:05:12.680 --> 00:05:17.040
So this wall just disappears.

00:05:17.040 --> 00:05:18.790
Now, what's going to happen?

00:05:18.790 --> 00:05:22.350
Well, as soon as I blow away
this wall, this is very much

00:05:22.350 --> 00:05:25.210
not an isostatic process.

00:05:25.210 --> 00:05:25.700
Right?

00:05:25.700 --> 00:05:27.250
All hell's going
to break loose.

00:05:27.250 --> 00:05:29.350
I'm going to blow away this
wall, and you know, the

00:05:29.350 --> 00:05:33.020
