00:05:42.580 --> 00:05:44.180
While these guys don't
know anything.

00:05:44.180 --> 00:05:45.690
They don't know anything until
they come over here and say,

00:05:45.690 --> 00:05:46.680
oh, no wall.

00:05:46.680 --> 00:05:48.140
So the pressure is in flux.

00:05:48.140 --> 00:05:51.000
Even the volume is in flux, as
these guys make their way

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:55.990
across the entire expanse
of the new volume.

00:05:55.990 --> 00:05:57.800
So everything is in flux.

00:05:57.800 --> 00:05:58.580
Right?

00:05:58.580 --> 00:05:59.820
And so what's our new volume?

00:05:59.820 --> 00:06:04.520
If we call this volume,
what's this?

00:06:04.520 --> 00:06:06.330
This is now 2 times
the volume.

00:06:09.120 --> 00:06:12.230
Let's think about some of the
other state variables we know.

00:06:12.230 --> 00:06:14.800
We know that the pressure
is going to go down.

00:06:14.800 --> 00:06:16.450
We can even relate it, because
we know that our

00:06:16.450 --> 00:06:17.670
volume is twice it.

00:06:17.670 --> 00:06:19.170
Is 2 times the volume.

00:06:19.170 --> 00:06:22.330
What about the temperature?

00:06:22.330 --> 00:06:23.890
Well, the temperature change.

00:06:23.890 --> 00:06:26.620
Temperature is average kinetic
energy, right?

00:06:26.620 --> 00:06:28.790
Or it's a measure of average
kinetic energy.

00:06:28.790 --> 00:06:31.910
So all of these molecules
here, each of them have

00:06:31.910 --> 00:06:32.700
kinetic energy.

00:06:32.700 --> 00:06:35.930
They could be different amounts
of kinetic energy, but

00:06:35.930 --> 00:06:38.410
temperature is a measure of
average kinetic energy.

00:06:38.410 --> 00:06:41.140
Now, if I blow away this wall,
does that change the kinetic

00:06:41.140 --> 00:06:42.680
energy of these molecules?

00:06:42.680 --> 00:06:43.310
No!

00:06:43.310 --> 00:06:44.670
It doesn't change it at all.

00:06:44.670 --> 00:06:46.700
So the temperature
is constant.

00:06:46.700 --> 00:06:51.480
So if this is T1, then the
